From: arm64-mthp-autopilot <mthp-autopilot@example.com>
Date: Thu, 12 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] ebpf: v3.0 — VMA-behaviour-driven promotion, remove name gating

Zero-application-code-modification policy violation fix.

PROBLEM
=======
v2.0 used process name (comm) as a gate on promotion order.
Any ML application not in the hardcoded name list (darknet, onnxruntime,
yolov8, inference_engine, detect, my_yolo, ...) was classified
APPCLASS_GENERIC and received permanently degraded promotion:

  VMA 512 KB–1 MB  →  ORDER_16KB  (should be ORDER_64KB)
  VMA 4 MB–8 MB    →  ORDER_64KB  (should be ORDER_2MB)
  hot_region ≥128  →  ORDER_64KB cap (should be ORDER_2MB)

Additionally, the GENERIC early-exit (skip faults 1–4) created a cache
starvation bug: any VMA first faulted during the skipped window was
inserted into the VMA cache at ORDER_4KB and served 256 subsequent faults
from that stale entry.

PRINCIPLE
=========
The VMA is the classifier.  If a process has a 6 MB anonymous VMA,
it wants large pages — regardless of whether it is named "python" or
"darknet".  Anonymous + large = wants 2MB.  This is a physical fact
about the memory access pattern, not a property of the process name.

CHANGES
=======

1. classify_vma(): remove APPCLASS_GENERIC penalty for 512KB–1MB anon
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   OLD:
     if (size >= 512KB) {
         if (app_class != APPCLASS_GENERIC)
             return ORDER_64KB;
         return ORDER_16KB;  ← GENERIC gets 16KB
     }

   NEW:
     if (size >= 512KB)
         return ORDER_64KB;  ← everyone gets 64KB

   Impact: any unknown ML process with a 512KB–1MB anonymous VMA (e.g.
   intermediate activations, NCHW buffers) now gets 64KB pages.
   64KB contiguous PTE = 16× TLB reach improvement on Cortex-A76.

2. hot_region_adjust(): remove app_class gate at HOT_THRESHOLD_3
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   OLD:
     if (fault_count >= 128) {
         if (app_class == ML || Media || DB || Server)
             order = ORDER_2MB;
         else
             order = ORDER_64KB;  ← GENERIC capped at 64KB forever
     }

   NEW:
     if (fault_count >= 128)
         order = ORDER_2MB;  ← any process, 128 faults = hot = 2MB

   Impact: unknown ML processes that hammer the same memory region
   (weight tensors, persistent activation buffers) now reach 2MB pages
   after 128 faults to that 2MB-aligned region.

   Rationale: 128 faults to a single 2MB region is empirical proof the
   process is actively using that memory.  Process name is irrelevant
   at this point — the access behaviour proves the classification.

3. Remove GENERIC early-exit (faults 1–4 skip)
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   OLD:
     if (cls->flags == APPCLASS_GENERIC && cls->total_faults < 4) {
         cls->total_faults++;
         return 0;  ← skip VMA lookup for first 4 faults
     }

   NEW:
     (removed entirely)

   The early-exit was added to save bpf_find_vma() cost on brand-new
   GENERIC processes.  With the VMA cache, the fast path costs ~50 ns
   (a hash lookup) after the first fault to a region.  The performance
   gain from skipping 4 faults is negligible; the bug it created was not:

   BUG: If a VMA was first accessed during faults 1–4 (while early-exit
   was active), the VMA cache was NOT populated.  On fault 5, the fault
   handler would do a full bpf_find_vma() and cache the result.  So far
   so good.  But if fault 5 landed on a DIFFERENT VMA than faults 1–4,
   the original VMA was never cached at all.  Subsequent faults to it
   would each do bpf_find_vma() — the cache miss path — but worse, the
   early-exit path had incremented total_faults without populating the
   cache, so the LRU map for that VMA region showed miss but the count
   was off, potentially falling back to 4KB permanently.

4. vma_cache_entry_v3: store ideal_order not post-guard order
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

   OLD:
     cache->chosen_order = order;  ← stored after buddy guard applied

   NEW:
     cache->ideal_order = ideal;   ← stored before buddy guard

   The buddy guard runs fresh on every fault from the cache_key.
   Under v2.0, if fault N happened under fragmentation (buddy guard
   stepped 2MB→64KB) and that post-guard result was cached, then faults
   N+1 through N+255 would all be served ORDER_64KB even after
   compaction restored plenty of 2MB blocks.

   v3.0 caches the ideal (pre-guard) order.  The guard always runs fresh.
   This means a hot tensor VMA that was temporarily stepped down due to
   fragmentation automatically recovers to 2MB once memory is compacted.

WHAT IS NOT CHANGED
===================
- classify_comm() is kept for the ONE remaining tiebreaker: anonymous
  VMAs in the 4–8MB band.  Known ML/Media/DB apps get ORDER_2MB; others
  get ORDER_64KB (still 16× improvement, and hot_region will upgrade
  to 2MB after 128 faults if the region is actually hot).

- The buddy guard itself is unchanged.  Memory safety is not relaxed.

- File-backed VMA classification is unchanged.

- The frag_index adaptive thresholds are unchanged.

PROMOTION TABLE — v2.0 vs v3.0 for APPCLASS_GENERIC
=====================================================

  VMA size     | Type      | v2.0 order | v3.0 order | Gain
  -------------|-----------|-----------|-----------|------------------------
  64–128 KB    | anon      | 4KB       | 4KB       | (below THRESH_MIN)
  128–512 KB   | anon      | 16KB      | 16KB      | same
  512KB–1MB    | anon      | 16KB      | 64KB      | ← 4× TLB reach gain
  1–4 MB       | anon      | 64KB      | 64KB      | same
  4–8 MB       | anon      | 64KB      | 64KB      | same (tiebreaker zone)
  8–32 MB      | anon      | 2MB       | 2MB       | same
  ≥ 32 MB      | anon      | 2MB       | 2MB       | same
  after 128 faults (hot)   | 64KB cap  | 2MB       | ← 32× TLB reach gain

Signed-off-by: arm64-mthp-autopilot v3.0
---
 ebpf/auto_classifier_kern.c | multiple changes as described above

diff --git a/ebpf/auto_classifier_kern.c b/ebpf/auto_classifier_kern.c
--- a/ebpf/auto_classifier_kern.c  (v2.0)
+++ b/ebpf/auto_classifier_kern.c  (v3.0)

@@ classify_vma() — anonymous 512KB-1MB band @@

-    if (size >= (512 * 1024)) {
-        /* v2.0: 64KB for all non-generic (was only ML/BROWSER) */
-        if (app_class != APPCLASS_GENERIC)
-            return ORDER_64KB;
-        return ORDER_16KB;    /* ← BUG: GENERIC gets 16KB here */
-    }
+    /* v3.0: 64KB for ALL processes at 512KB–1MB — no name discrimination */
+    if (size >= (512 * 1024))
+        return ORDER_64KB;

@@ hot_region_adjust() — HOT_THRESHOLD_3 app_class gate @@

-    if (hr->fault_count >= HOT_THRESHOLD_3 && base_order < ORDER_2MB) {
-        /* Very hot: try 2MB if app class supports it */
-        if (app_class == APPCLASS_ML ||
-            app_class == APPCLASS_MEDIA ||
-            app_class == APPCLASS_DATABASE ||
-            app_class == APPCLASS_SERVER)
-            order = ORDER_2MB;
-        else
-            order = ORDER_64KB;    /* ← BUG: GENERIC capped at 64KB */
-    }
+    /* v3.0: 128 faults = hot = 2MB for ANY process */
+    if (hr->fault_count >= HOT_THRESHOLD_3 && order < ORDER_2MB)
+        order = ORDER_2MB;

@@ hot_region_adjust() — function signature @@

-static __always_inline __u32
-hot_region_adjust(__u32 pid, __u64 addr, __u32 base_order, __u32 app_class)
+static __always_inline __u32
+hot_region_adjust(__u32 pid, __u64 addr, __u32 base_order)
+/* app_class parameter removed — no longer used in the hot path */

@@ auto_classify_fault() — remove GENERIC early-exit @@

-    /*
-     * v2.0: Early exit for GENERIC with < 4 faults (was 8).
-     */
-    if (cls->flags == APPCLASS_GENERIC && cls->total_faults < 4) {
-        cls->total_faults++;
-        return 0;
-    }

@@ vma_cache_entry — store ideal_order separately @@

-struct vma_cache_entry {
-    __u32 pid;
-    __u32 chosen_order;   /* ← post-guard order (bug: caches fragmentation) */
+struct vma_cache_entry_v3 {
+    __u32 pid;
+    __u32 ideal_order;    /* ← pre-guard order (v3.0: guard runs fresh) */
     __u64 vma_start;
     __u64 vma_end;
     __u64 vma_flags;
     __u32 app_class;
     __u32 hit_count;
     __u32 fault_count;
     __u32 _pad;
 };

@@ cache hit path — use ideal_order @@

-        order   = cached->chosen_order;
-        ideal   = order;
+        ideal   = cached->ideal_order;   /* pre-guard ideal */
+        order   = ideal;
         /* buddy guard still runs below — no caching of guard result */

@@ cache populate — store ideal not post-guard @@

         struct vma_cache_entry new_cache = {
             .pid          = pid,
-            .chosen_order = order,  /* was post-guard */
+            .ideal_order  = ideal,  /* v3.0: store pre-guard */
